Note:
==============================================================================
FALCON-NTRUSOLVE : recursive cyclotomic tower descent solving f*G - g*F = q
==============================================================================

Per Falcon spec sections 3.8.2 and 3.8.5 (ntrugen module of the reference
implementation), the NTRU equation

  f * G - g * F = q   in Z[X]/(X^n + 1)

is solved by descending the tower of cyclotomic rings

  K_n = Q[X]/(X^n + 1)
  K_{n/2} = Q[X]/(X^(n/2) + 1)
  ...
  K_1 = Q

via the field-norm map  N(a) = a * a_bar  where a_bar(X) = a(-X) is the
Galois conjugate.  The image of f in K_{n/2} (and so on down) shrinks by a
factor of n/2 in degree at each step.  At the base K_1 the equation is a
plain Bezout identity over Z and we solve it directly with the extended
Euclidean algorithm.  On the way back up, the reference (F', G') found at
half size is lifted into K_n and then Babai-reduced against (f, g) until
the resulting (F, G) is short enough to satisfy the Falcon norm bound.

Storage convention (v3 - zint internal descent):
  - The PUBLIC entry point ntru_solve takes int16 arrays for f, g (input)
    and writes int16 arrays for F, G (output).  The final F, G at the top
    of the descent are bounded by the Falcon norm acceptance criterion
    (||(F,G)||^2 <= 16823 * q / n) and so fit comfortably in int16.
  - All INTERNAL recursive descent operates on multi-precision integer
    polynomials (zint coefficient form) so that coefficient magnitudes
    can grow without bound as the descent deepens.  Float64 was insufficient
    because at depth 9 of Falcon-1024 the field-norm coefficients exceed
    ~2^2560 and the 53-bit mantissa silently truncates them, producing
    Bezout failures that cascade as keygen attempt exhaustion.
  - Sign handling is sign-magnitude on each zint; addition and subtraction
    dispatch on the sign pair.

Algorithm outline (Falcon spec Algorithm 6):
  ntru_solve(f, g, n):
    if n == 1:
      use extended Euclidean over Z to find (F, G) with f*G - g*F = q
      return (F, G)
    let f' = field_norm(f), g' = field_norm(g) in K_{n/2}
    (F', G') = ntru_solve(f', g', n/2)
    Lift (F', G') back to K_n by the "split" map and Babai-reduce
    against (f, g).  Re-check norm; if it is still too large, fail.
    return (F, G)

Public entry: ntru_solve(arena, f, g, n, F_out, G_out) -> Integer
Returns 1 on success, 0 on precision failure or no-solution at the
descent base.

Security_Scope (module-wide):
  All inputs and outputs of ntru_solve are SECRET (Falcon private key
  material).  The descent uses zint multi-precision arithmetic whose
  inner loop iteration counts depend on operand bit length only, not
  on operand values.  The Babai reduction iteration count is data
  dependent and is a Falcon-permitted leakage path.
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/memory_core.runa" as Memory
Import "runtime/core/memory/arena.runa" as Arena
Import "compiler/frontend/import_system/crypto/pq/falcon_zint.runa" as Z
Import "compiler/frontend/import_system/crypto/pq/falcon_zint_poly.runa" as ZP
Import "compiler/frontend/import_system/crypto/pq/falcon_fp.runa" as FP
Import "compiler/frontend/import_system/crypto/pq/falcon_fft.runa" as FFT

Note:
==============================================================================
EXTENDED EUCLIDEAN ALGORITHM OVER Z (base case n = 1)
==============================================================================
Solves f * G - g * F = q where f, g, F, G are integers.  At the base
case the coefficients have already been driven down to Int64 range by
repeated field-norm contraction (the field norm of a small Gaussian
polynomial in K_1 is a single small integer).
:End Note

Process called "ntrusolve_extgcd" takes a as Integer, b as Integer, x_out as Integer, y_out as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Extended Euclidean: given (a, b) returns (g, x, y) with a*x + b*y = g
    where g = gcd(|a|, |b|).  We store x at x_out, y at y_out, and return g.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Iterative formulation.  Tracks (old_r, r), (old_s, s), (old_t, t) and
    rotates until r becomes zero.  Handles negative inputs by canonicalising
    sign at the start and re-applying signs at the end so the returned g is
    nonnegative and the Bezout identity holds with the original a, b.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    O(log min(|a|, |b|)) divisions.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Inputs are SECRET; control flow depends on quotient sequence which is
    a Falcon-mandated leakage path.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let sa be 1
    Let sb be 1
    Let aa be a
    Let bb be b
    If aa is less than 0:
        Set sa to 0 minus 1
        Set aa to 0 minus aa
    End If
    If bb is less than 0:
        Set sb to 0 minus 1
        Set bb to 0 minus bb
    End If
    Let old_r be aa
    Let r be bb
    Let old_s be 1
    Let s be 0
    Let old_t be 0
    Let t be 1
    While r is not equal to 0:
        Let q be old_r divided by r
        Let tmp_r be r
        Set r to old_r minus q multiplied by r
        Set old_r to tmp_r
        Let tmp_s be s
        Set s to old_s minus q multiplied by s
        Set old_s to tmp_s
        Let tmp_t be t
        Set t to old_t minus q multiplied by t
        Set old_t to tmp_t
    End While
    Note: old_r = gcd, old_s * aa + old_t * bb = old_r
    Note: Re-apply sign so the identity holds with the original a, b.
    Let x_val be old_s multiplied by sa
    Let y_val be old_t multiplied by sb
    Memory.memory_set_int64(x_out, 0, x_val)
    Memory.memory_set_int64(y_out, 0, y_val)
    Return old_r
End Process

Note:
==============================================================================
BASE CASE n = 1 OVER ZINT
==============================================================================
:End Note

Process called "ntrusolve_zint_extgcd" takes arena as Integer, a_z as Integer, b_z as Integer, x_out_ptr as Integer, y_out_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Extended Euclidean over zint: given (a, b) compute (g, x, y) with
    a*x + b*y = g where g = gcd(|a|, |b|).  Stores the freshly allocated
    zints for x and y at x_out_ptr, y_out_ptr.  Returns g (also a zint).
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Iterative formulation matching the Int64 extgcd but with all
    quantities as zints:
      (old_r, r) = (|a|, |b|)
      (old_s, s) = (1, 0)
      (old_t, t) = (0, 1)
      while r != 0:
        q = old_r / r          (zint quotient)
        (old_r, r) = (r, old_r - q*r)
        (old_s, s) = (s, old_s - q*s)
        (old_t, t) = (t, old_t - q*t)
      return (old_r, sa*old_s, sb*old_t)
    Sign post-pass restores the Bezout identity for the original
    (signed) a, b.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    O(log(min(|a|, |b|))) zint divisions.  Each division is bit-serial
    over the operand bit length; total cost is dominated by the deepest
    descent level where coefficient bit length tops out.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    SECRET.  Loop count and inner cost depend on bit length only.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let sa be Z.zint_get_sign(a_z)
    Let sb be Z.zint_get_sign(b_z)

    Let old_r be Z.zint_copy(arena, a_z)
    Z.zint_abs(old_r)
    Let r be Z.zint_copy(arena, b_z)
    Z.zint_abs(r)

    Let old_s be Z.zint_from_int(arena, 1)
    Let s be Z.zint_from_int(arena, 0)
    Let old_t be Z.zint_from_int(arena, 0)
    Let t be Z.zint_from_int(arena, 1)

    While Z.zint_is_zero(r) is equal to 0:
        Let q_ptr be Arena.arena_allocate(arena, 8)
        Let rem_ptr be Arena.arena_allocate(arena, 8)
        Z.zint_divmod(arena, old_r, r, q_ptr, rem_ptr)
        Let q be Memory.memory_get_int64(q_ptr, 0)
        Let new_r be Memory.memory_get_int64(rem_ptr, 0)

        Note: (old_r, r) = (r, new_r)
        Set old_r to r
        Set r to new_r

        Note: (old_s, s) = (s, old_s - q*s)
        Let q_s be Z.zint_mul(arena, q, s)
        Let new_s_cap be Z.zint_get_used(old_s)
        Let qs_u be Z.zint_get_used(q_s)
        If qs_u is greater than new_s_cap:
            Set new_s_cap to qs_u
        End If
        Set new_s_cap to new_s_cap plus 2
        Let new_s be Z.zint_create(arena, new_s_cap)
        Z.zint_sub(new_s, old_s, q_s)
        Set old_s to s
        Set s to new_s

        Note: (old_t, t) = (t, old_t - q*t)
        Let q_t be Z.zint_mul(arena, q, t)
        Let new_t_cap be Z.zint_get_used(old_t)
        Let qt_u be Z.zint_get_used(q_t)
        If qt_u is greater than new_t_cap:
            Set new_t_cap to qt_u
        End If
        Set new_t_cap to new_t_cap plus 2
        Let new_t be Z.zint_create(arena, new_t_cap)
        Z.zint_sub(new_t, old_t, q_t)
        Set old_t to t
        Set t to new_t
    End While

    Note: Re-apply sign so identity holds with original a, b.
    If sa is equal to 1:
        Z.zint_neg(old_s)
    End If
    If sb is equal to 1:
        Z.zint_neg(old_t)
    End If
    Memory.memory_set_int64(x_out_ptr, 0, old_s)
    Memory.memory_set_int64(y_out_ptr, 0, old_t)
    Return old_r
End Process

Process called "ntru_solve_base_n1" takes arena as Integer, f_poly as Integer, g_poly as Integer, F_poly as Integer, G_poly as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Solve f*G - g*F = q at n = 1.  f and g are single zint coefficients
    that can be arbitrarily large (the K_1 image of Falcon-sampled f, g
    after log2(n) field-norm descents is bounded by roughly ||f||^n
    in absolute value, i.e. ~2^3000 bits for Falcon-512 and ~2^6000 bits
    for Falcon-1024).
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    1. Reject if f or g is zero (degenerate input).
    2. Run zint extgcd on (f_z, g_z) to obtain (d, u, v) with
       f*u + g*v = d.
    3. q must be divisible by d; otherwise no integer (F, G) exists
       satisfying f*G - g*F = q.  Reject (caller restarts).
    4. F = -v * (q / d); G = u * (q / d).
    5. Write F, G as single-coefficient zints back into F_poly, G_poly.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Dominated by the inner zint extgcd, which itself is dominated by
    zint long division on operands of ~3000 to ~6000 bits depending
    on parameter set.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    SECRET.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let f_z be ZP.zint_poly_get(f_poly, 0)
    Let g_z be ZP.zint_poly_get(g_poly, 0)

    If Z.zint_is_zero(f_z) is equal to 1:
        Return 0
    End If
    If Z.zint_is_zero(g_z) is equal to 1:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let u_ptr be Arena.arena_allocate(arena, 8)
    Let v_ptr be Arena.arena_allocate(arena, 8)
    Let d_z be proc ntrusolve_zint_extgcd with arena, f_z, g_z, u_ptr, v_ptr
    If Z.zint_is_zero(d_z) is equal to 1:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: q must be divisible by d.  We test by zint divmod and checking
    Note: that the remainder is zero.
    Let q_z be Z.zint_from_int(arena, 12289)
    Let qdiv_ptr be Arena.arena_allocate(arena, 8)
    Let qrem_ptr be Arena.arena_allocate(arena, 8)
    Z.zint_divmod(arena, q_z, d_z, qdiv_ptr, qrem_ptr)
    Let q_div_d be Memory.memory_get_int64(qdiv_ptr, 0)
    Let q_rem be Memory.memory_get_int64(qrem_ptr, 0)
    If Z.zint_is_zero(q_rem) is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let u_z be Memory.memory_get_int64(u_ptr, 0)
    Let v_z be Memory.memory_get_int64(v_ptr, 0)

    Note: F = -v * q_div_d; G = u * q_div_d.
    Let G_new be Z.zint_mul(arena, u_z, q_div_d)
    Let v_q be Z.zint_mul(arena, v_z, q_div_d)
    Z.zint_neg(v_q)
    Let F_new be v_q

    ZP.zint_poly_set(F_poly, 0, F_new)
    ZP.zint_poly_set(G_poly, 0, G_new)
    Return 1
End Process

Note:
==============================================================================
LIFT : embed K_{n/2} solution into K_n
==============================================================================
Given the half-size solution (F', G') in K_{n/2} satisfying

    f_norm * G' - g_norm * F' = q

where f_norm = N(f), g_norm = N(g) in K_{n/2}, the canonical lift to K_n
satisfying f * G - g * F = q is

    F(X) = F'(X^2) * g_bar(X)
    G(X) = G'(X^2) * f_bar(X)

where f_bar(X) = f(-X) is the Galois conjugate.  This identity is
straightforward to verify by substituting the definitions of f_norm and
g_norm and reducing modulo (X^n + 1).
:End Note

Process called "ntrusolve_zint_lift_even_squared" takes arena as Integer, half_poly as Integer, half_n as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Embed a K_{n/2} zint polynomial p(Y) as p(X^2) in K_n.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Allocate a length-n zint polynomial; the k-th coefficient of the
    half polynomial goes to position 2k of the full polynomial.  Odd
    positions are zero.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Linear in n.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    SECRET.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let full_n be half_n multiplied by 2
    Let bytes be full_n multiplied by 8
    Let full be Arena.arena_allocate(arena, bytes)
    If full is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Memory.memory_zero(full, bytes)
    Let k be 0
    While k is less than half_n:
        Let v be ZP.zint_poly_get(half_poly, k)
        Let copy_v be Z.zint_copy(arena, v)
        ZP.zint_poly_set(full, k multiplied by 2, copy_v)
        Set k to k plus 1
    End While
    Let idx be 0
    While idx is less than full_n:
        Let cur be ZP.zint_poly_get(full, idx)
        If cur is equal to 0:
            ZP.zint_poly_set(full, idx, Z.zint_from_int(arena, 0))
        End If
        Set idx to idx plus 1
    End While
    Return full
End Process

Note:
==============================================================================
BABAI ROUNDING REDUCTION OF (F, G) AGAINST (f, g) -- zint flavour
==============================================================================
The Babai reduction step (Falcon spec Algorithm 6, line 6) is

    k = round( (F * adj(f) + G * adj(g)) / (f * adj(f) + g * adj(g)) )
    (F, G) <- (F - k*f, G - k*g)

iterated until k becomes zero.  In the canonical Pornin reference
(falcon/ntru.c BABAI_REDUCE) the division is performed in the FFT
slot domain at fp53 precision: each slot of the numerator is divided
by the corresponding (real-valued) denominator slot, then inverse-
FFTed back to coefficient form.

This module is the zint (multi-precision integer) flavour of the
descent.  The division above is computed by
zint_poly_divide_by_kn_denominator (in falcon_zint_poly.runa) via
exact K_n polynomial division, descending the cyclotomic tower down
to K_1 where each rational division is rounded to nearest integer by
zint_poly_round_div_scalar.

The K_n denominator D = f*adj(f) + g*adj(g) has only even-power-of-X
coefficients (cross-term parity cancellation under Galois conjugation
in K_n).  The top-level divider exploits this by skipping one level
of the general recursion: it computes D, projects to K_{n/2} via
extract_even, splits the numerator into even/odd halves under
Y = X^2, and recursively divides each half by the projected denom in
K_{n/2}.  At the recursive level the denominator has no special
structure, so the recursion multiplies by adj_D at each step to
re-establish the even-coefficient property of D*adj(D), descending
all the way to K_1.

With exact K_n polynomial division the Babai quotient is mathematically
precise to within a single coefficient round, so each iteration
strictly reduces ||(F, G)||^2 by the full denominator bit width and
the loop converges in O(1) iterations (typically 1 on Falcon-distributed
inputs).  The max_iter = 32 guard catches pathological data only.
:End Note

Process called "ntrusolve_zint_poly_norm_sq_scalar" takes arena as Integer, poly as Integer, n as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Compute sum_{k=0}^{n-1} poly[k]^2 (a single zint integer; not a
    polynomial in K_n).  Retained as an inspection helper for the
    norm-debugging code paths; the Babai reduction no longer uses
    this scalar quantity (it uses K_n polynomial division instead).
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    For each coefficient, multiply it by itself (always nonnegative)
    and add to a running zint accumulator.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    O(n) zint multiplies + adds.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    SECRET.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let acc be Z.zint_create(arena, 8)
    Let k be 0
    While k is less than n:
        Let c be ZP.zint_poly_get(poly, k)
        Let sq be Z.zint_mul(arena, c, c)
        Let acc_u be Z.zint_get_used(acc)
        Let sq_u be Z.zint_get_used(sq)
        Let new_cap be acc_u
        If sq_u is greater than new_cap:
            Set new_cap to sq_u
        End If
        Set new_cap to new_cap plus 2
        Let new_acc be Z.zint_create(arena, new_cap)
        Z.zint_add(new_acc, acc, sq)
        Set acc to new_acc
        Set k to k plus 1
    End While
    Return acc
End Process

Note:
==============================================================================
HYBRID FFT-fp53 + ZINT BABAI REDUCTION (Pornin reference algorithm)
==============================================================================

Pornin's Falcon reference (falcon/keygen.c BABAI_REDUCE) accelerates the
Babai inner step by performing the K_n rational division
  k = round( (F*adj(f) + G*adj(g)) / (f*adj(f) + g*adj(g)) )
in the FFT slot domain at fp53 precision: each complex slot of the
numerator is divided by the corresponding (real-valued) denominator
slot, then inverse-FFT'd back to coefficient form.  This collapses the
O(n^2 log n) exact-zint polynomial division to an O(n log n) FFT
pipeline.

When coefficient magnitudes outgrow fp53 (~53 mantissa bits, conservative
threshold 50 bits to leave a 3-bit round-off margin), the FFT path
silently truncates and produces an incorrect k.  We detect this BEFORE
running the FFT by checking the bit length of every coefficient of F, G,
f, g; on rejection we fall back to the exact-zint kernel for that single
iteration only.  Coefficient bit lengths grow approximately linearly
with descent depth, so the FFT path serves the early shallow iterations
(where it's a major win) and the zint fallback covers the deep tail.

Per-iteration cost when fp53 succeeds:
  - 4 forward FFTs (f, g, F, G), reused across many Babai iterations
    via a per-call cache passed through the loop scope.
  - O(n) pointwise multiplies for numerator and denominator.
  - O(n) pointwise division.
  - 1 inverse FFT.
  - 2 K_n polynomial multiplies (k*f, k*g) in zint for the F, G update.
  Total: O(n log n) FFT plus O(n^2) zint mul for the update.

Per-iteration cost on fp53 rejection (fallback):
  - Same as the original pure-zint kernel: O(n^2 log n) per iteration.
:End Note

Process called "ntrusolve_max_bits_in_polys" takes f_poly as Integer, g_poly as Integer, F_poly as Integer, G_poly as Integer, n as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Compute the maximum bit length across all coefficients of f, g, F, G.
    The Babai numerator F*conj(f) + G*conj(g) has total bit length at
    most max_bits(F,G) + max_bits(f,g) + log2(n) under K_n convolution;
    likewise the denominator.  Caller uses this to decide whether the
    fp53 FFT path is precision-safe.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Four passes of zint_poly_max_bit_length (one per polynomial) tracking
    the running maximum.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Linear in n across four polynomials.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    SECRET; bit length leakage is Falcon-permitted.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let max_bits be ZP.zint_poly_max_bit_length(f_poly, n)
    Let gb be ZP.zint_poly_max_bit_length(g_poly, n)
    If gb is greater than max_bits:
        Set max_bits to gb
    End If
    Let Fb be ZP.zint_poly_max_bit_length(F_poly, n)
    If Fb is greater than max_bits:
        Set max_bits to Fb
    End If
    Let Gb be ZP.zint_poly_max_bit_length(G_poly, n)
    If Gb is greater than max_bits:
        Set max_bits to Gb
    End If
    Return max_bits
End Process

Process called "ntrusolve_log2_ceil" takes n as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Return ceil(log2(n)) for n >= 1.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Iteratively halve n until it reaches 1, counting passes.  Add a one
    to the count when n is not an exact power of two so that the result
    is ceil rather than floor.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    O(log n) integer ops.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Public.
    @End Security_Scope
    If n is less than or equal to 1:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let k be 0
    Let v be n
    Let pow2 be 1
    While pow2 is less than v:
        Set pow2 to pow2 multiplied by 2
        Set k to k plus 1
    End While
    Return k
End Process

Process called "ntrusolve_fft_babai_step" takes arena as Integer, f_poly as Integer, g_poly as Integer, F_poly as Integer, G_poly as Integer, n as Integer, did_update_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Perform one Babai reduction iteration in the FFT slot domain at fp53.
    Returns 1 on success (k computed and F, G updated in place; if k was
    identically zero, did_update_ptr is set to 0 and the caller halts),
    or 0 on precision rejection (caller falls back to the exact-zint
    kernel for this iteration).
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Step-by-step:

      1. Precision check.  Let max_bits = max coefficient bit length
         across f, g, F, G.  The numerator F*conj(f) + G*conj(g) and
         the denominator f*conj(f) + g*conj(g) have coefficient bit
         lengths bounded by 2*max_bits + log2(n) + 1.  We require this
         bound to fit inside 50 bits (fp53 minus a 3-bit safety margin).
         If not, return 0.

      2. Build FFT-domain images of f, g, F, G.

      3. Compute f_conj_fft = conj(f_fft), g_conj_fft = conj(g_fft) by
         pointwise conjugation (the FFT of the Galois conjugate of a
         real-coefficient cyclotomic polynomial is exactly the complex
         conjugate of the slot, mirroring Pornin's reference).

      4. Compute the FFT-domain denominator
            D_fft[i] = f_fft[i] * conj(f_fft[i]) + g_fft[i] * conj(g_fft[i])
                     = |f_fft[i]|^2 + |g_fft[i]|^2
         (a real non-negative number per slot).

      5. Compute the FFT-domain numerator
            N_fft[i] = F_fft[i] * conj(f_fft[i]) + G_fft[i] * conj(g_fft[i]).

      6. Slot-wise quotient k_fft[i] = N_fft[i] / D_fft[i].  Because D is
         real this is just a Float division of real and imaginary parts.

      7. Inverse FFT of k_fft.  Round each real part to the nearest
         integer; build a length-n zint polynomial k_poly.

      8. Convergence test: if every coefficient of k_poly is zero, set
         *did_update_ptr = 0 and return 1.

      9. Otherwise update F <- F - k_poly * f, G <- G - k_poly * g in
         zint (exact integer math; the inexactness is confined to the
         FFT-rounded k).  Copy the new F, G back into the caller's
         polynomial slots.  Set *did_update_ptr = 1 and return 1.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Four forward FFTs + one inverse FFT + O(n) pointwise + two K_n
    zint multiplies per iteration.  O(n log n) FFT pipeline dominates
    for small n; O(n^2) zint mul dominates for large n.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    SECRET.
    @End Security_Scope
    Note: Step 1: pick a uniform scaling baseline for the FFT lift.
    Note: We compute the max used-limb count across all four polynomials
    Note: and lift each coefficient to its top 62 bits at that
    Note: baseline.  This is Pornin's reference scaling: the resulting
    Note: N / D ratio in the FFT slot domain is correct because both
    Note: numerator and denominator scale by the same factor S^2.
    Note: A precision-rejection path remains for the case where ALL
    Note: four polynomials have used == 0 (only the trivial zero
    Note: polynomial), which would yield an all-zero FFT denominator;
    Note: we treat it as a converged (k = 0) iteration.
    Let max_used_f be ZP.zint_poly_max_used(f_poly, n)
    Let max_used_g be ZP.zint_poly_max_used(g_poly, n)
    Let max_used_F be ZP.zint_poly_max_used(F_poly, n)
    Let max_used_G be ZP.zint_poly_max_used(G_poly, n)
    Let baseline_used be max_used_f
    If max_used_g is greater than baseline_used:
        Set baseline_used to max_used_g
    End If
    If max_used_F is greater than baseline_used:
        Set baseline_used to max_used_F
    End If
    If max_used_G is greater than baseline_used:
        Set baseline_used to max_used_G
    End If
    Note: baseline_used must be at least 2 so that we always have a
    Note: well-defined top-limb / low-limb pair for the float conversion.
    If baseline_used is less than 2:
        Set baseline_used to 2
    End If
    Note: If f or g is identically zero we cannot proceed in the FFT
    Note: kernel because the denominator would be zero; signal failure
    Note: so the caller falls back to the exact-zint kernel which
    Note: handles this edge case via its zero-poly short circuit.
    If max_used_f is equal to 0:
        Memory.memory_set_int64(did_update_ptr, 0, 0)
        Return 0
    End If
    If max_used_g is equal to 0:
        Memory.memory_set_int64(did_update_ptr, 0, 0)
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Step 2: FFT-domain images.  Each FFT buffer = 16*n bytes.
    Let buf_bytes be n multiplied by 16
    Let f_fft be Arena.arena_allocate(arena, buf_bytes)
    Let g_fft be Arena.arena_allocate(arena, buf_bytes)
    Let F_fft be Arena.arena_allocate(arena, buf_bytes)
    Let G_fft be Arena.arena_allocate(arena, buf_bytes)
    If G_fft is equal to 0:
        Memory.memory_set_int64(did_update_ptr, 0, 0)
        Return 0
    End If

    Let load_f_ok be ZP.zint_poly_to_fft(arena, f_poly, n, f_fft, baseline_used)
    If load_f_ok is equal to 0:
        Memory.memory_set_int64(did_update_ptr, 0, 0)
        Return 0
    End If
    Let load_g_ok be ZP.zint_poly_to_fft(arena, g_poly, n, g_fft, baseline_used)
    If load_g_ok is equal to 0:
        Memory.memory_set_int64(did_update_ptr, 0, 0)
        Return 0
    End If
    Let load_F_ok be ZP.zint_poly_to_fft(arena, F_poly, n, F_fft, baseline_used)
    If load_F_ok is equal to 0:
        Memory.memory_set_int64(did_update_ptr, 0, 0)
        Return 0
    End If
    Let load_G_ok be ZP.zint_poly_to_fft(arena, G_poly, n, G_fft, baseline_used)
    If load_G_ok is equal to 0:
        Memory.memory_set_int64(did_update_ptr, 0, 0)
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Step 3: conjugates of f, g in FFT domain.
    Let f_conj be Arena.arena_allocate(arena, buf_bytes)
    Let g_conj be Arena.arena_allocate(arena, buf_bytes)
    proc FFT.fft_conj with f_fft, f_conj, n
    proc FFT.fft_conj with g_fft, g_conj, n

    Note: Step 4: denominator D[i] = |f[i]|^2 + |g[i]|^2 (real value
    Note: per slot).  Compute as fp_mul of (f*conj(f) + g*conj(g))
    Note: pointwise: store result as a real value with zero imaginary
    Note: part (the imaginary parts of f*conj(f) and g*conj(g) cancel
    Note: exactly per Parseval).
    Let denom_fft be Arena.arena_allocate(arena, buf_bytes)
    Let zero_v be proc FP.fp_zero
    Let si be 0
    While si is less than n:
        Let fr be proc FFT.fft_get_real with f_fft, si
        Let fi be proc FFT.fft_get_imag with f_fft, si
        Let gr be proc FFT.fft_get_real with g_fft, si
        Let gi be proc FFT.fft_get_imag with g_fft, si
        Let fr2 be proc FP.fp_mul with fr, fr
        Let fi2 be proc FP.fp_mul with fi, fi
        Let gr2 be proc FP.fp_mul with gr, gr
        Let gi2 be proc FP.fp_mul with gi, gi
        Let fmag be proc FP.fp_add with fr2, fi2
        Let gmag be proc FP.fp_add with gr2, gi2
        Let dmag be proc FP.fp_add with fmag, gmag
        proc FFT.fft_set_real with denom_fft, si, dmag
        proc FFT.fft_set_imag with denom_fft, si, zero_v
        Set si to si plus 1
    End While

    Note: Step 5: numerator N[i] = F[i]*conj(f[i]) + G[i]*conj(g[i])
    Let numer_fft be Arena.arena_allocate(arena, buf_bytes)
    Let ni be 0
    While ni is less than n:
        Let Fr be proc FFT.fft_get_real with F_fft, ni
        Let Fi be proc FFT.fft_get_imag with F_fft, ni
        Let fcr be proc FFT.fft_get_real with f_conj, ni
        Let fci be proc FFT.fft_get_imag with f_conj, ni
        Note: F * conj(f) = (Fr + Fi i)(fcr + fci i)
        Note:             = (Fr*fcr - Fi*fci) + (Fr*fci + Fi*fcr) i
        Let p1 be proc FP.fp_mul with Fr, fcr
        Let p2 be proc FP.fp_mul with Fi, fci
        Let nr_F be proc FP.fp_sub with p1, p2
        Let p3 be proc FP.fp_mul with Fr, fci
        Let p4 be proc FP.fp_mul with Fi, fcr
        Let ni_F be proc FP.fp_add with p3, p4

        Let Gr be proc FFT.fft_get_real with G_fft, ni
        Let Gi be proc FFT.fft_get_imag with G_fft, ni
        Let gcr be proc FFT.fft_get_real with g_conj, ni
        Let gci be proc FFT.fft_get_imag with g_conj, ni
        Let q1 be proc FP.fp_mul with Gr, gcr
        Let q2 be proc FP.fp_mul with Gi, gci
        Let nr_G be proc FP.fp_sub with q1, q2
        Let q3 be proc FP.fp_mul with Gr, gci
        Let q4 be proc FP.fp_mul with Gi, gcr
        Let ni_G be proc FP.fp_add with q3, q4

        Let nr_tot be proc FP.fp_add with nr_F, nr_G
        Let ni_tot be proc FP.fp_add with ni_F, ni_G
        proc FFT.fft_set_real with numer_fft, ni, nr_tot
        proc FFT.fft_set_imag with numer_fft, ni, ni_tot
        Set ni to ni plus 1
    End While

    Note: Step 6: pointwise division k_fft[i] = N[i] / D[i].
    Note: D[i] is real and non-negative; division reduces to dividing
    Note: real and imaginary parts of N[i] by D[i].
    Let k_fft be Arena.arena_allocate(arena, buf_bytes)
    Let qi be 0
    While qi is less than n:
        Let nr be proc FFT.fft_get_real with numer_fft, qi
        Let nim be proc FFT.fft_get_imag with numer_fft, qi
        Let d_v be proc FFT.fft_get_real with denom_fft, qi
        Note: If d_v is exactly zero (degenerate f=g=0 case) we install
        Note: zero in the quotient slot so the resulting k is zero and
        Note: the Babai loop sees no update.
        Let zero_r be proc FP.fp_zero
        Let d_is_zero be proc FP.fp_eq with d_v, zero_r
        Let kr be 0
        Let kim be 0
        If d_is_zero is equal to 1:
            Set kr to zero_r
            Set kim to zero_r
        Otherwise:
            Set kr to proc FP.fp_div with nr, d_v
            Set kim to proc FP.fp_div with nim, d_v
        End If
        proc FFT.fft_set_real with k_fft, qi, kr
        proc FFT.fft_set_imag with k_fft, qi, kim
        Set qi to qi plus 1
    End While

    Note: Step 7: inverse FFT and rounding into a zint polynomial.
    Let k_poly be ZP.fft_to_zint_poly(arena, k_fft, n)
    If k_poly is equal to 0:
        Memory.memory_set_int64(did_update_ptr, 0, 0)
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Step 8: convergence check.
    Let all_zero be 1
    Let ci be 0
    While ci is less than n:
        Let kc be ZP.zint_poly_get(k_poly, ci)
        If Z.zint_is_zero(kc) is equal to 0:
            Set all_zero to 0
        End If
        Set ci to ci plus 1
    End While
    If all_zero is equal to 1:
        Memory.memory_set_int64(did_update_ptr, 0, 0)
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Step 9: update F <- F - k*f, G <- G - k*g (exact zint math).
    Let kf be ZP.zint_poly_mul(arena, k_poly, f_poly, n)
    Let kg be ZP.zint_poly_mul(arena, k_poly, g_poly, n)
    Let new_F be ZP.zint_poly_sub(arena, F_poly, kf, n)
    Let new_G be ZP.zint_poly_sub(arena, G_poly, kg, n)
    Let cp be 0
    While cp is less than n:
        ZP.zint_poly_set(F_poly, cp, ZP.zint_poly_get(new_F, cp))
        ZP.zint_poly_set(G_poly, cp, ZP.zint_poly_get(new_G, cp))
        Set cp to cp plus 1
    End While
    Memory.memory_set_int64(did_update_ptr, 0, 1)
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "ntrusolve_zint_babai_iteration" takes arena as Integer, f_poly as Integer, g_poly as Integer, F_poly as Integer, G_poly as Integer, f_bar as Integer, g_bar as Integer, n as Integer, did_update_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Perform one Babai iteration entirely in exact zint arithmetic.  Used
    as the fallback when the FFT-fp53 path rejects on precision.  Sets
    *did_update_ptr to 1 if F, G were updated, 0 if k was identically
    zero (convergence).  Returns 1 on success, 0 on failure.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Standard kernel:
      1. numer = F * f_bar + G * g_bar in K_n.
      2. k     = round( numer / (f*adj(f) + g*adj(g)) ) in K_n via
                 zint_poly_divide_by_kn_denominator.
      3. If k is identically zero, signal convergence.
      4. F <- F - k*f, G <- G - k*g (copied back into the caller's slots).
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    O(n^2 log n) zint multiplications per iteration at the bit length
    determined by the descent level.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    SECRET.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let Ff_bar be ZP.zint_poly_mul(arena, F_poly, f_bar, n)
    Let Gg_bar be ZP.zint_poly_mul(arena, G_poly, g_bar, n)
    Let numer be ZP.zint_poly_add(arena, Ff_bar, Gg_bar, n)

    Let k_poly be ZP.zint_poly_divide_by_kn_denominator(arena, numer, f_poly, g_poly, n)
    If k_poly is equal to 0:
        Memory.memory_set_int64(did_update_ptr, 0, 0)
        Return 0
    End If

    Let all_zero be 1
    Let ci be 0
    While ci is less than n:
        Let kc be ZP.zint_poly_get(k_poly, ci)
        If Z.zint_is_zero(kc) is equal to 0:
            Set all_zero to 0
        End If
        Set ci to ci plus 1
    End While

    If all_zero is equal to 1:
        Memory.memory_set_int64(did_update_ptr, 0, 0)
        Return 1
    End If

    Let kf be ZP.zint_poly_mul(arena, k_poly, f_poly, n)
    Let kg be ZP.zint_poly_mul(arena, k_poly, g_poly, n)
    Let new_F be ZP.zint_poly_sub(arena, F_poly, kf, n)
    Let new_G be ZP.zint_poly_sub(arena, G_poly, kg, n)
    Let cp be 0
    While cp is less than n:
        ZP.zint_poly_set(F_poly, cp, ZP.zint_poly_get(new_F, cp))
        ZP.zint_poly_set(G_poly, cp, ZP.zint_poly_get(new_G, cp))
        Set cp to cp plus 1
    End While
    Memory.memory_set_int64(did_update_ptr, 0, 1)
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "ntrusolve_fft_babai_reduce_fft_form" takes arena as Integer, f_fft as Integer, g_fft as Integer, F_fft as Integer, G_fft as Integer, f_conj_fft as Integer, g_conj_fft as Integer, denom_fft as Integer, n as Integer, max_iter as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Inner Babai reduction loop operating ENTIRELY in the FFT slot domain
    at fp53.  Inputs and outputs stay in FFT form across all iterations;
    no zint allocations, no zint multiplications.  This is the
    performance-critical kernel of the Falcon NTRU descent: the
    coefficient-space update F <- F - k*f becomes the pointwise
    F_fft[i] <- F_fft[i] - k_fft[i] * f_fft[i] in O(n) complex ops, and
    the only O(n log n) work per iteration is one inverse FFT for the
    convergence test plus one forward FFT to re-load the rounded k as
    an integer polynomial in FFT form.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Pre-conditions:
      - f_fft, g_fft: forward FFTs of f, g with a UNIFORM scaling
        baseline (see zint_poly_to_fft).  Same baseline must have been
        applied to F_fft, G_fft so the slot-wise ratios cancel.
      - f_conj_fft = elementwise complex conjugate of f_fft.
      - g_conj_fft = elementwise complex conjugate of g_fft.
      - denom_fft[i] = |f_fft[i]|^2 + |g_fft[i]|^2 (real-valued,
        imaginary slot is zero by Parseval).
      - F_fft, G_fft: forward FFTs of F, G at the same baseline.  These
        buffers are MUTATED in place across iterations.

    Per iteration:
      1. Compute numer_fft[i] = F_fft[i] * f_conj_fft[i]
                              + G_fft[i] * g_conj_fft[i].
         Standard complex multiplication accumulated into a fresh slot.
      2. Compute k_quot_fft[i] = numer_fft[i] / denom_fft[i].
         Since denom_fft is real, this is two scalar divisions per slot.
      3. Copy k_quot_fft into k_inverse (because fft_inverse mutates
         in place and we still need a fresh buffer for the round-trip).
      4. fft_inverse(k_inverse).  The 1/n scaling pass is included.
      5. Round each real slot of k_inverse to the nearest Int64.  This
         is the integer k polynomial.  Track all_zero flag and a
         max-magnitude bound for downstream re-scaling decisions.
      6. If all_zero is 1: converged, return iter (the number of
         completed updates).
      7. Otherwise: rebuild k_fft_unscaled by loading the Int64 k
         coefficients as Floats with zero imaginary parts into a fresh
         FFT buffer, then forward-FFT in place.  This is the FFT of
         the freshly-rounded k polynomial WITHOUT any baseline scaling
         (k itself is small, bounded by the round-off of numer/denom).
      8. Apply the update F_fft[i] -= k_fft_unscaled[i] * f_fft[i] and
         G_fft[i] -= k_fft_unscaled[i] * g_fft[i] pointwise.  Reason
         (sketch):
            F[X] = SUM F_fft[i] * exp(...) * S          (S = baseline scale)
            f[X] = SUM f_fft[i] * exp(...) * S
            k[X] = SUM k_fft_unscaled[i] * exp(...)     (no S)
            (k * f)[X] / S = SUM k_fft_unscaled[i] * f_fft[i] * exp(...)
         So F_fft[i] -= k_fft_unscaled[i] * f_fft[i] gives the correct
         updated F_fft at the same baseline scaling as the input.

    The loop terminates when k rounds to identically zero (the Babai
    convergence criterion) or when iter reaches max_iter.  Returns the
    number of successful iterations on convergence, or 0 if max_iter is
    exhausted without convergence (caller treats as failure).

    Precision policy: this kernel assumes the bit length of f, g, F, G
    at the input baseline fits comfortably inside fp53.  Caller MUST
    enforce the precision check (max_bits + log2(n) < 50) before
    invoking this routine; if the check fails, caller falls through to
    the pure-zint kernel.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Per iteration:
      - O(n) complex multiplies and adds for numer and the F, G update.
      - O(n) real divisions for the quotient slot computation.
      - O(n log n) for one inverse FFT + one forward FFT.
      - O(n) Int64 round + reload.
    Total: O(n log n) per iteration.  No O(n^2) zint multiplications.
    Convergence is typically 1 iteration for Falcon-distributed inputs.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    SECRET.  All slot-domain operations are fp53 floating point;
    rounding behaviour depends only on the bit pattern of the operands,
    which Falcon classifies as a permitted side channel (the FFT
    pipeline is the reference implementation pattern).
    @End Security_Scope
    Let buf_bytes be n multiplied by 16
    Let numer_fft be Arena.arena_allocate(arena, buf_bytes)
    Let k_quot_fft be Arena.arena_allocate(arena, buf_bytes)
    Let k_inverse be Arena.arena_allocate(arena, buf_bytes)
    Let k_unscaled_fft be Arena.arena_allocate(arena, buf_bytes)
    If k_unscaled_fft is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let k_coeffs be Arena.arena_allocate(arena, n multiplied by 8)
    If k_coeffs is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let iter be 0
    Let stop be 0
    Let zero_v be proc FP.fp_zero
    While stop is equal to 0:
        If iter is greater than or equal to max_iter:
            Note: Convergence failure; caller decides whether this is
            Note: fatal (pure-zint fallback can handle pathological data).
            Return 0
        End If

        Note: Step 1: numerator slot N[i] = F[i]*conj(f)[i] + G[i]*conj(g)[i]
        Let i be 0
        While i is less than n:
            Let Fr be proc FFT.fft_get_real with F_fft, i
            Let Fi be proc FFT.fft_get_imag with F_fft, i
            Let fcr be proc FFT.fft_get_real with f_conj_fft, i
            Let fci be proc FFT.fft_get_imag with f_conj_fft, i
            Let p1 be proc FP.fp_mul with Fr, fcr
            Let p2 be proc FP.fp_mul with Fi, fci
            Let nr_F be proc FP.fp_sub with p1, p2
            Let p3 be proc FP.fp_mul with Fr, fci
            Let p4 be proc FP.fp_mul with Fi, fcr
            Let ni_F be proc FP.fp_add with p3, p4

            Let Gr be proc FFT.fft_get_real with G_fft, i
            Let Gi be proc FFT.fft_get_imag with G_fft, i
            Let gcr be proc FFT.fft_get_real with g_conj_fft, i
            Let gci be proc FFT.fft_get_imag with g_conj_fft, i
            Let q1 be proc FP.fp_mul with Gr, gcr
            Let q2 be proc FP.fp_mul with Gi, gci
            Let nr_G be proc FP.fp_sub with q1, q2
            Let q3 be proc FP.fp_mul with Gr, gci
            Let q4 be proc FP.fp_mul with Gi, gcr
            Let ni_G be proc FP.fp_add with q3, q4

            Let nr_tot be proc FP.fp_add with nr_F, nr_G
            Let ni_tot be proc FP.fp_add with ni_F, ni_G
            proc FFT.fft_set_real with numer_fft, i, nr_tot
            proc FFT.fft_set_imag with numer_fft, i, ni_tot
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While

        Note: Step 2: k_quot[i] = N[i] / denom[i] (denom is real-only).
        Let qi be 0
        While qi is less than n:
            Let nr be proc FFT.fft_get_real with numer_fft, qi
            Let nim be proc FFT.fft_get_imag with numer_fft, qi
            Let d_v be proc FFT.fft_get_real with denom_fft, qi
            Let d_is_zero be proc FP.fp_eq with d_v, zero_v
            Let kr be 0
            Let kim be 0
            If d_is_zero is equal to 1:
                Set kr to zero_v
                Set kim to zero_v
            Otherwise:
                Set kr to proc FP.fp_div with nr, d_v
                Set kim to proc FP.fp_div with nim, d_v
            End If
            proc FFT.fft_set_real with k_quot_fft, qi, kr
            proc FFT.fft_set_imag with k_quot_fft, qi, kim
            Set qi to qi plus 1
        End While

        Note: Step 3: copy k_quot_fft into k_inverse before iFFT
        Note: (fft_inverse mutates in place).
        proc FFT.fft_copy with k_inverse, k_quot_fft, n

        Note: Step 4: inverse FFT to coefficient domain.
        Let inv_ok be proc FFT.fft_inverse with arena, k_inverse, n
        If inv_ok is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If

        Note: Step 5: round each real coefficient to nearest Int64.
        Let all_zero be 1
        Let ci be 0
        While ci is less than n:
            Let r_f be proc FFT.fft_get_real with k_inverse, ci
            Let k_int be proc FP.fp_to_int_round with r_f
            Memory.memory_set_int64(k_coeffs, ci multiplied by 8, k_int)
            If k_int is not equal to 0:
                Set all_zero to 0
            End If
            Set ci to ci plus 1
        End While

        Note: Step 6: convergence check.
        If all_zero is equal to 1:
            Return iter
        End If

        Note: Step 7: rebuild k_fft (unscaled) by loading Int64 k
        Note: coefficients into Floats and forward-FFTing.
        Memory.memory_zero(k_unscaled_fft, buf_bytes)
        Let li be 0
        While li is less than n:
            Let k_int_v be Memory.memory_get_int64(k_coeffs, li multiplied by 8)
            Let k_f be proc FP.fp_from_int with k_int_v
            proc FFT.fft_set_real with k_unscaled_fft, li, k_f
            proc FFT.fft_set_imag with k_unscaled_fft, li, zero_v
            Set li to li plus 1
        End While
        Let fwd_ok be proc FFT.fft_forward with arena, k_unscaled_fft, n
        If fwd_ok is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If

        Note: Step 8: F_fft[i] -= k_fft[i] * f_fft[i],
        Note:         G_fft[i] -= k_fft[i] * g_fft[i] pointwise.
        Let ui be 0
        While ui is less than n:
            Let kfr be proc FFT.fft_get_real with k_unscaled_fft, ui
            Let kfi be proc FFT.fft_get_imag with k_unscaled_fft, ui

            Let ffr be proc FFT.fft_get_real with f_fft, ui
            Let ffi be proc FFT.fft_get_imag with f_fft, ui
            Note: (kfr + kfi i)(ffr + ffi i) = (kfr*ffr - kfi*ffi) + (kfr*ffi + kfi*ffr) i
            Let af1 be proc FP.fp_mul with kfr, ffr
            Let af2 be proc FP.fp_mul with kfi, ffi
            Let kf_r be proc FP.fp_sub with af1, af2
            Let af3 be proc FP.fp_mul with kfr, ffi
            Let af4 be proc FP.fp_mul with kfi, ffr
            Let kf_i be proc FP.fp_add with af3, af4

            Let Fr2 be proc FFT.fft_get_real with F_fft, ui
            Let Fi2 be proc FFT.fft_get_imag with F_fft, ui
            Let new_Fr be proc FP.fp_sub with Fr2, kf_r
            Let new_Fi be proc FP.fp_sub with Fi2, kf_i
            proc FFT.fft_set_real with F_fft, ui, new_Fr
            proc FFT.fft_set_imag with F_fft, ui, new_Fi

            Let gfr be proc FFT.fft_get_real with g_fft, ui
            Let gfi be proc FFT.fft_get_imag with g_fft, ui
            Let bg1 be proc FP.fp_mul with kfr, gfr
            Let bg2 be proc FP.fp_mul with kfi, gfi
            Let kg_r be proc FP.fp_sub with bg1, bg2
            Let bg3 be proc FP.fp_mul with kfr, gfi
            Let bg4 be proc FP.fp_mul with kfi, gfr
            Let kg_i be proc FP.fp_add with bg3, bg4

            Let Gr2 be proc FFT.fft_get_real with G_fft, ui
            Let Gi2 be proc FFT.fft_get_imag with G_fft, ui
            Let new_Gr be proc FP.fp_sub with Gr2, kg_r
            Let new_Gi be proc FP.fp_sub with Gi2, kg_i
            proc FFT.fft_set_real with G_fft, ui, new_Gr
            proc FFT.fft_set_imag with G_fft, ui, new_Gi

            Set ui to ui plus 1
        End While

        Set iter to iter plus 1
    End While
    Return iter
End Process

Process called "ntrusolve_zint_babai_reduce" takes arena as Integer, f_poly as Integer, g_poly as Integer, F_poly as Integer, G_poly as Integer, n as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Hybrid Babai reduction shim matching the Pornin reference Falcon
    structure.  Attempts the FAST PATH (FFT-form Babai with no zint
    inner loop) first; on precision rejection at this descent level
    falls back to the exact-zint kernel which can handle arbitrarily
    large coefficients.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Fast path:
      1. Precision check.  Compute max_bits across f, g, F, G.  Numer
         and denom slot magnitudes are bounded by ~2*max_bits + log2(n).
         We require this to fit in 50 bits (fp53 minus 3-bit margin).
         If not, fall through to the pure-zint loop.
      2. Allocate FFT buffers for f, g, F, G, f_conj, g_conj, denom.
      3. Compute baseline limb count and lift each zint polynomial into
         its FFT buffer with that uniform baseline.
      4. Compute f_conj_fft, g_conj_fft by elementwise conjugation.
      5. Compute denom_fft[i] = |f_fft[i]|^2 + |g_fft[i]|^2.
      6. Call ntrusolve_fft_babai_reduce_fft_form for up to max_iter=32
         iterations.  This is the hot inner loop; it operates entirely
         in fp53 with O(n log n) per iteration.
      7. After convergence, inverse-FFT F_fft, G_fft back into zint
         polynomials.  Because we force baseline_used = 2 in the lift,
         the Float values stored at each slot are the EXACT integer
         coefficient values (precision gate ensures each fits in <= 2
         limbs = 62 bits).  Inverse FFT then yields the same exact
         integers (modulo fp53 round-off, which the integer rounding
         absorbs).  No rescaling pass is needed.

    Slow path (zint kernel):
      Same iterated loop as before, computing the K_n polynomial
      division exactly with zint_poly_divide_by_kn_denominator.  Used
      only when the precision check rejects the FFT path, which occurs
      at the deepest tower levels where coefficients exceed ~2^50.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Fast path: O(n log n) per iteration, typically 1 iteration.  Memory
    is O(n) for the seven FFT buffers.
    Slow path: O(n^2 log n) per iteration via exact zint K_n division.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    SECRET.  Loop count and FFT-vs-zint dispatch leak the coefficient
    bit length, a Falcon-permitted side channel.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let max_iter be 32

    Note: Step 1: precision check on input bit lengths.  Numerator and
    Note: denominator products have bit length <= 2*max_bits + log2(n) + 1.
    Note: We require fit in 50 bits to keep fp53 round-off below 1 LSB
    Note: of an integer-rounded k coefficient.
    Let max_bits be proc ntrusolve_max_bits_in_polys with f_poly, g_poly, F_poly, G_poly, n
    Let log2n be proc ntrusolve_log2_ceil with n
    Let needed_bits be 2 multiplied by max_bits
    Set needed_bits to needed_bits plus log2n
    Set needed_bits to needed_bits plus 1

    Let use_fft_path be 0
    If needed_bits is less than or equal to 50:
        Set use_fft_path to 1
    End If

    Let f_bar be ZP.zint_poly_conjugate(arena, f_poly, n)
    Let g_bar be ZP.zint_poly_conjugate(arena, g_poly, n)

    If use_fft_path is equal to 1:
        Note: Fast path: lift to FFT once, do the Babai loop in FFT, lift
        Note: back once.  We use baseline_used = 2 unconditionally so the
        Note: zint -> Float mapping is the EXACT integer value (the
        Note: precision gate above ensures every coefficient fits in
        Note: the top62-of-2-limbs window, i.e. <= ~62 bits).  With no
        Note: per-coefficient scaling factor, the inverse-FFT recovery
        Note: at the end of the loop reads off the integer values
        Note: directly without rescaling, which is the only stable
        Note: extraction when Babai has shrunk F, G to small magnitudes.
        Let max_used_f be ZP.zint_poly_max_used(f_poly, n)
        Let max_used_g be ZP.zint_poly_max_used(g_poly, n)
        Let max_used_F be ZP.zint_poly_max_used(F_poly, n)
        Let max_used_G be ZP.zint_poly_max_used(G_poly, n)
        Let max_used_all be max_used_f
        If max_used_g is greater than max_used_all:
            Set max_used_all to max_used_g
        End If
        If max_used_F is greater than max_used_all:
            Set max_used_all to max_used_F
        End If
        If max_used_G is greater than max_used_all:
            Set max_used_all to max_used_G
        End If

        Note: Tighter precision check: with baseline_used = 2 the lift
        Note: stores top62 bits of |z| as a Float, which is exact only
        Note: when used <= 2.  If any coefficient overflows 2 limbs we
        Note: must defer to the zint kernel.  This is a stricter
        Note: condition than the bit-length gate above and so is
        Note: enforced unconditionally here.
        If max_used_all is greater than 2:
            Set use_fft_path to 0
        End If

        Let baseline_used be 2

        Note: f or g identically zero ==> denom = 0 ==> fast path cannot
        Note: progress.  Defer to zint loop which handles the edge case.
        If max_used_f is equal to 0:
            Set use_fft_path to 0
        End If
        If max_used_g is equal to 0:
            Set use_fft_path to 0
        End If

        If use_fft_path is equal to 1:
            Let buf_bytes be n multiplied by 16
            Let f_fft be Arena.arena_allocate(arena, buf_bytes)
            Let g_fft be Arena.arena_allocate(arena, buf_bytes)
            Let F_fft be Arena.arena_allocate(arena, buf_bytes)
            Let G_fft be Arena.arena_allocate(arena, buf_bytes)
            Let f_conj_fft be Arena.arena_allocate(arena, buf_bytes)
            Let g_conj_fft be Arena.arena_allocate(arena, buf_bytes)
            Let denom_fft be Arena.arena_allocate(arena, buf_bytes)
            If denom_fft is equal to 0:
                Set use_fft_path to 0
            End If

            If use_fft_path is equal to 1:
                Note: Lift each zint poly into FFT at the shared baseline.
                Let load_f be ZP.zint_poly_to_fft(arena, f_poly, n, f_fft, baseline_used)
                Let load_g be ZP.zint_poly_to_fft(arena, g_poly, n, g_fft, baseline_used)
                Let load_F be ZP.zint_poly_to_fft(arena, F_poly, n, F_fft, baseline_used)
                Let load_G be ZP.zint_poly_to_fft(arena, G_poly, n, G_fft, baseline_used)
                If load_G is equal to 0:
                    Set use_fft_path to 0
                End If

                If use_fft_path is equal to 1:
                    Note: Conjugates of f and g in FFT domain.
                    proc FFT.fft_conj with f_fft, f_conj_fft, n
                    proc FFT.fft_conj with g_fft, g_conj_fft, n

                    Note: denom_fft[i] = |f|^2 + |g|^2 (real value).
                    Let zero_v be proc FP.fp_zero
                    Let si be 0
                    While si is less than n:
                        Let fr be proc FFT.fft_get_real with f_fft, si
                        Let fi be proc FFT.fft_get_imag with f_fft, si
                        Let gr be proc FFT.fft_get_real with g_fft, si
                        Let gi be proc FFT.fft_get_imag with g_fft, si
                        Let fr2 be proc FP.fp_mul with fr, fr
                        Let fi2 be proc FP.fp_mul with fi, fi
                        Let gr2 be proc FP.fp_mul with gr, gr
                        Let gi2 be proc FP.fp_mul with gi, gi
                        Let fmag be proc FP.fp_add with fr2, fi2
                        Let gmag be proc FP.fp_add with gr2, gi2
                        Let dmag be proc FP.fp_add with fmag, gmag
                        proc FFT.fft_set_real with denom_fft, si, dmag
                        proc FFT.fft_set_imag with denom_fft, si, zero_v
                        Set si to si plus 1
                    End While

                    Note: Drive the inner loop entirely in FFT form.
                    Let iter_count be proc ntrusolve_fft_babai_reduce_fft_form with arena, f_fft, g_fft, F_fft, G_fft, f_conj_fft, g_conj_fft, denom_fft, n, max_iter
                    If iter_count is less than 0:
                        Set use_fft_path to 0
                    End If

                    If use_fft_path is equal to 1:
                        Note: Inverse FFT F_fft, G_fft and recover zint
                        Note: coefficients.  Since the FFT round-trip
                        Note: preserves integer-valued polynomials up to
                        Note: fp53 rounding, and our F, G have shrunk in
                        Note: magnitude after Babai, we extract by inverse
                        Note: FFT and then rescaling by the baseline
                        Note: factor (which is what the original lift
                        Note: applied).
                        Let inv_F_ok be proc FFT.fft_inverse with arena, F_fft, n
                        If inv_F_ok is equal to 0:
                            Return 0
                        End If
                        Let inv_G_ok be proc FFT.fft_inverse with arena, G_fft, n
                        If inv_G_ok is equal to 0:
                            Return 0
                        End If

                        Note: With baseline_used = 2 the original lift
                        Note: stored the EXACT integer value of each
                        Note: coefficient as a Float (provided used <= 2,
                        Note: which the gate enforces).  The inverse FFT
                        Note: round-trip preserves the integer values up
                        Note: to fp53 rounding, and after Babai the
                        Note: coefficient magnitudes have only shrunk,
                        Note: so the integer round of the inverse-FFT
                        Note: real part recovers the post-Babai
                        Note: coefficient directly with no rescaling.
                        Let ki be 0
                        While ki is less than n:
                            Let Fr_v be proc FFT.fft_get_real with F_fft, ki
                            Let Gr_v be proc FFT.fft_get_real with G_fft, ki
                            Let F_int be proc FP.fp_to_int_round with Fr_v
                            Let G_int be proc FP.fp_to_int_round with Gr_v
                            Let F_z be Z.zint_from_int(arena, F_int)
                            Let G_z be Z.zint_from_int(arena, G_int)
                            proc ZP.zint_poly_set with F_poly, ki, F_z
                            proc ZP.zint_poly_set with G_poly, ki, G_z
                            Set ki to ki plus 1
                        End While
                        Return 1
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End If

    Note: Slow path (pure-zint kernel) used when the precision check
    Note: rejected the fast path or any allocation failed.
    Let iter be 0
    Let stop be 0

    Let did_update_ptr be Arena.arena_allocate(arena, 8)
    If did_update_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    While stop is equal to 0:
        If iter is greater than or equal to max_iter:
            Set stop to 1
        End If
        If stop is equal to 0:
            Memory.memory_set_int64(did_update_ptr, 0, 0)
            Let zint_ok be proc ntrusolve_zint_babai_iteration with arena, f_poly, g_poly, F_poly, G_poly, f_bar, g_bar, n, did_update_ptr
            If zint_ok is equal to 0:
                Return 0
            End If
            Let did_update be Memory.memory_get_int64(did_update_ptr, 0)
            If did_update is equal to 0:
                Set stop to 1
            Otherwise:
                Set iter to iter plus 1
            End If
        End If
    End While
    Return 1
End Process

Note:
==============================================================================
INTERNAL RECURSIVE DESCENT : ntru_solve_zint
==============================================================================
Operates entirely on zint coefficient-form polynomials so that the
coefficient magnitudes can grow without bound across descent levels.
:End Note

Process called "ntru_solve_zint" takes arena as Integer, f_poly as Integer, g_poly as Integer, n as Integer, F_poly as Integer, G_poly as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Solve the NTRU equation f*G - g*F = q in Z[X]/(X^n+1) via tower
    descent, fully in zint coefficient-form polynomials.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Recursive case n >= 2:
      1. Compute f_norm = N(f), g_norm = N(g) in K_{n/2}.
      2. Allocate half-size F_half, G_half buffers.
      3. Recurse on (f_norm, g_norm, n/2) -> (F_half, G_half).
      4. Lift via F_full = F_half(X^2) * g_bar(X), G_full = G_half(X^2) * f_bar(X).
      5. Copy F_full, G_full coefficients into F_poly, G_poly.
      6. Babai-reduce (F_poly, G_poly) against (f, g).
    Base case n=1: extended Euclidean over Z (see ntru_solve_base_n1).
    Returns 1 on success, 0 on precision failure or unsolvable Bezout.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    O(n^2 log n) per level (zint polynomial multiply dominates) times
    O(log n) levels.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    SECRET.
    @End Security_Scope
    If n is equal to 1:
        Return proc ntru_solve_base_n1 with arena, f_poly, g_poly, F_poly, G_poly
    End If

    Let half_n be n shifted right by 1

    Let f_norm be ZP.zint_poly_field_norm(arena, f_poly, n)
    Let g_norm be ZP.zint_poly_field_norm(arena, g_poly, n)
    If g_norm is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Allocate half-size solution buffers.
    Let F_half be ZP.zint_poly_create(arena, half_n, 1)
    Let G_half be ZP.zint_poly_create(arena, half_n, 1)
    If G_half is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let rec_ok be proc ntru_solve_zint with arena, f_norm, g_norm, half_n, F_half, G_half
    If rec_ok is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Lift.  F_full = F_half(X^2) * g_bar(X), G_full = G_half(X^2) * f_bar(X).
    Let F_x2 be proc ntrusolve_zint_lift_even_squared with arena, F_half, half_n
    Let G_x2 be proc ntrusolve_zint_lift_even_squared with arena, G_half, half_n
    Let f_bar be ZP.zint_poly_conjugate(arena, f_poly, n)
    Let g_bar be ZP.zint_poly_conjugate(arena, g_poly, n)

    Let F_lifted be ZP.zint_poly_mul(arena, F_x2, g_bar, n)
    Let G_lifted be ZP.zint_poly_mul(arena, G_x2, f_bar, n)

    Let cp be 0
    While cp is less than n:
        ZP.zint_poly_set(F_poly, cp, ZP.zint_poly_get(F_lifted, cp))
        ZP.zint_poly_set(G_poly, cp, ZP.zint_poly_get(G_lifted, cp))
        Set cp to cp plus 1
    End While

    Note: Babai-reduce against (f, g).
    Let red_ok be proc ntrusolve_zint_babai_reduce with arena, f_poly, g_poly, F_poly, G_poly, n
    If red_ok is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

Note:
==============================================================================
PUBLIC ENTRY POINT : ntru_solve  (int16 in, int16 out)
==============================================================================
:End Note

Process called "ntru_solve" takes arena as Integer, f_int as Integer, g_int as Integer, n as Integer, F_out as Integer, G_out as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Public NTRUSolve entry.  Accepts and produces int16 coefficient arrays
    for compatibility with the Falcon keygen orchestrator.  Internally
    creates a transient scratch arena (256 MiB), runs the zint descent
    inside it, copies the final (F, G) back to the caller's int16 buffers,
    then destroys the scratch arena.  This isolates the descent's large
    transient memory footprint from the caller's arena, avoiding the
    arena re-mmap pointer-invalidation hazard.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    1. arena_create a scratch arena large enough for the worst-case zint
       descent (256 MiB suffices for Falcon-1024).
    2. Build zint polynomials f_poly, g_poly from the int16 inputs.
    3. Allocate F_poly, G_poly zint polynomials (initially zero).
    4. Call ntru_solve_zint to perform the descent.
    5. Extract F_poly, G_poly to the caller's F_out, G_out via
       zint_poly_to_int_array.  Range rejection at this step is the
       keygen restart signal.
    6. Compute the int16 squared norm and reject if it exceeds the
       sanity bound (catches catastrophic precision failures even when
       individual coefficients fit in int16).
    7. arena_destroy the scratch arena and return the success flag.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Dominated by the recursive descent: O(n^2 log n) zint multiplies.
    The arena_create / arena_destroy pair costs one mmap + one munmap
    per call, which is negligible relative to the descent.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    All polynomials SECRET.  The scratch arena's munmap returns the
    pages to the kernel, scrubbing any residual zint limb data.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let scratch_cap be 1073741824
    Let scratch be Arena.arena_create(scratch_cap)
    If scratch is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let f_poly be ZP.zint_poly_from_int_array(scratch, f_int, n, 2)
    Let g_poly be ZP.zint_poly_from_int_array(scratch, g_int, n, 2)
    If g_poly is equal to 0:
        Arena.arena_destroy(scratch)
        Return 0
    End If

    Let F_poly be ZP.zint_poly_create(scratch, n, 1)
    Let G_poly be ZP.zint_poly_create(scratch, n, 1)
    If G_poly is equal to 0:
        Arena.arena_destroy(scratch)
        Return 0
    End If

    Let solve_ok be proc ntru_solve_zint with scratch, f_poly, g_poly, n, F_poly, G_poly
    If solve_ok is equal to 0:
        Arena.arena_destroy(scratch)
        Return 0
    End If

    Let F_extract be ZP.zint_poly_to_int_array(F_poly, F_out, n, 2)
    If F_extract is equal to 0:
        Arena.arena_destroy(scratch)
        Return 0
    End If
    Let G_extract be ZP.zint_poly_to_int_array(G_poly, G_out, n, 2)
    If G_extract is equal to 0:
        Arena.arena_destroy(scratch)
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Per Falcon spec section 3.8.1 the keygen acceptance criterion
    Note: is ||(g, -f, G, -F)||^2 <= ceil(2 * 16823 * q / n) where q=12289.
    Note: This bound is the per-key cumulant of the per-signature norm
    Note: budget; rejecting (F, G) that fails it is what guarantees the
    Note: subsequent sign-stage sampler never exhausts its rejection
    Note: window.  The shim already enforces the LARGER 2^40 sanity
    Note: bound implicitly (via the int16 range), so the only new gate
    Note: here is the tight Falcon bound on (F, G) PLUS (f, g).
    Let F_norm be 0
    Let G_norm be 0
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than n:
        Let off be i multiplied by 2
        Let Fc be Memory.memory_get_int16(F_out, off)
        Let Gc be Memory.memory_get_int16(G_out, off)
        Set F_norm to F_norm plus (Fc multiplied by Fc)
        Set G_norm to G_norm plus (Gc multiplied by Gc)
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Let f_norm be 0
    Let g_norm be 0
    Let j be 0
    While j is less than n:
        Let offj be j multiplied by 2
        Let fc be Memory.memory_get_int16(f_int, offj)
        Let gc be Memory.memory_get_int16(g_int, offj)
        Set f_norm to f_norm plus (fc multiplied by fc)
        Set g_norm to g_norm plus (gc multiplied by gc)
        Set j to j plus 1
    End While
    Let total_norm be F_norm plus G_norm
    Set total_norm to total_norm plus f_norm
    Set total_norm to total_norm plus g_norm

    Note: Falcon spec bound: per Pornin reference's falcon_l2bound[logn]
    Note: table.  This is the per-signature norm budget; (F, G) plus
    Note: (f, g) must satisfy ||v||^2 <= bound or the sign stage
    Note: sampler cannot meet its rejection criterion.
    Note: For Falcon-512 (logn=9): 34034726.
    Note: For Falcon-1024 (logn=10): 70265242.
    Let falcon_norm_bound be 34034726
    If n is equal to 1024:
        Set falcon_norm_bound to 70265242
    End If
    Arena.arena_destroy(scratch)
    If total_norm is greater than falcon_norm_bound:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return 1
End Process

Note:
==============================================================================
END falcon_ntrusolve
==============================================================================
:End Note
